scenarios.situation:
We had an outage yesterday and I need you to turn these raw Slack messages into a summary for an async update. People need to understand what happened, but this is not the final incident template yet.

@chen 14:02 — "payments service is throwing 500s, customers can't checkout"
@davis 14:05 — "I see the DB connection pool is exhausted on payments-db-primary"
@chen 14:08 — "scaling up read replicas now"
@martinez 14:11 — "got a customer escalation from Acme Corp, they have a $200k order stuck"
@davis 14:15 — "found it — the nightly analytics job didn't release its connections, been holding 80% of the pool since 03:00"
@chen 14:18 — "killed the analytics job, connections recovering"
@davis 14:22 — "pool back to normal, 500s stopped"
@martinez 14:25 — "Acme Corp order went through, confirming with their account manager"
@chen 14:30 — "we should add a connection timeout to the analytics job and set up an alert on pool utilization > 70%"
@davis 14:31 — "agreed, also maybe move analytics to the read replica so it can't starve production"

You could write this as a close retelling that keeps customer impact, diagnosis, fix, and prevention ideas connected to the moments where they appear. Or you could separate it into impact, duration, root cause, detection, mitigation steps, customer resolution, and action items. Which way would you handle this async update, and why?
